{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-8651a594b0ec1e32","type":"tool_result","content":"**[SETTLEMENT AGREEMENT AND GENERAL RELEASE OF ALL CLAIMS]{.underline}**\n\nDated: May 5, 2025\n\nPrepared by Engel & Associates, P.C. 700 SW Taylor Street, Suite 400, Portland, OR 97205\n\n**[PREAMBLE]{.underline}**\n\nThis Settlement Agreement and General Release of All Claims (\\\"Agreement\\\") is entered into as of May 5, 2025 (\\\"Effective Date\\\"), by and between:\n\n**Marcus R. Delano**, an individual residing at 1847 SE Hawthorne Boulevard, Portland, OR 97214 (hereinafter referred to as \\\"Delano\\\" or \\\"Employee\\\"); and\n\n**Greenleaf Organic Foods, Inc.**, an Oregon corporation with its principal place of business at 4200 NW Yeon Avenue, Portland, OR 97210 (hereinafter referred to as \\\"Greenleaf,\\\" \\\"the Company,\\\" or \\\"Employer\\\").\n\nDelano and Greenleaf are collectively referred to herein as \\\"the Parties\\\" and individually as a \\\"Party.\\\"\n\n**[RECITALS]{.underline}**\n\n**WHEREAS**, Delano was employed by Greenleaf from June 12, 2017, through March 14, 2025, a period of approximately seven years and nine months, during which time Delano served in progressively responsible roles within the Company\\'s operations division;\n\n**WHEREAS**, Delano was promoted to the position of Vice President of Supply Chain Operations effective January 1, 2020, and at the time of his separation from the Company, earned a base annual salary of Two Hundred Eighteen Thousand Dollars (\\$218,000.00), in addition to eligibility for performance-based incentive compensation and equity awards;\n\n**WHEREAS**, on November 8, 2024, Delano submitted a good-faith internal complaint to Greenleaf\\'s Human Resources Director, Leanne Foss, reporting concerns regarding cold-chain protocol failures at the Company\\'s Bend, Oregon distribution facility that Delano believed constituted potential violations of FDA food safety regulations, including but not limited to requirements under the Food Safety Modernization Act and applicable FDA guidance on temperature controls for perishable organic food products;\n\n**WHEREAS**,","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2243dbd6-f247-49ae-9765-e42e664078a9","uuid":"66512184-9dec-4f1a-883c-8e10ca19488a","timestamp":"2026-06-27T05:23:05.527Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"**[SETTLEMENT AGREEMENT AND GENERAL RELEASE OF ALL CLAIMS]{.underline}**\n\nDated: May 5, 2025\n\nPrepared by Engel & Associates, P.C. 700 SW Taylor Street, Suite 400, Portland, OR 97205\n\n**[PREAMBLE]{.underline}**\n\nThis Settlement Agreement and General Release of All Claims (\\\"Agreement\\\") is entered into as of May 5, 2025 (\\\"Effective Date\\\"), by and between:\n\n**Marcus R. Delano**, an individual residing at 1847 SE Hawthorne Boulevard, Portland, OR 97214 (hereinafter referred to as \\\"Delano\\\" or \\\"Employee\\\"); and\n\n**Greenleaf Organic Foods, Inc.**, an Oregon corporation with its principal place of business at 4200 NW Yeon Avenue, Portland, OR 97210 (hereinafter referred to as \\\"Greenleaf,\\\" \\\"the Company,\\\" or \\\"Employer\\\").\n\nDelano and Greenleaf are collectively referred to herein as \\\"the Parties\\\" and individually as a \\\"Party.\\\"\n\n**[RECITALS]{.underline}**\n\n**WHEREAS**, Delano was employed by Greenleaf from June 12, 2017, through March 14, 2025, a period of approximately seven years and nine months, during which time Delano served in progressively responsible roles within the Company\\'s operations division;\n\n**WHEREAS**, Delano was promoted to the position of Vice President of Supply Chain Operations effective January 1, 2020, and at the time of his separation from the Company, earned a base annual salary of Two Hundred Eighteen Thousand Dollars (\\$218,000.00), in addition to eligibility for performance-based incentive compensation and equity awards;\n\n**WHEREAS**, on November 8, 2024, Delano submitted a good-faith internal complaint to Greenleaf\\'s Human Resources Director, Leanne Foss, reporting concerns regarding cold-chain protocol failures at the Company\\'s Bend, Oregon distribution facility that Delano believed constituted potential violations of FDA food safety regulations, including but not limited to requirements under the Food Safety Modernization Act and applicable FDA guidance on temperature controls for perishable organic food products;\n\n**WHEREAS**,","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
