lano\\'s spouse or domestic partner, provided that such individual agrees to maintain the confidentiality of the information;\n>\n> \\(ii\\) to Delano\\'s legal counsel at Engel & Associates, P.C., or any successor legal counsel retained by Delano;\n>\n> \\(iii\\) to Delano\\'s tax advisor, accountant, or financial advisor, solely for the purpose of obtaining tax, accounting, or financial advice, provided that such advisor agrees to maintain the confidentiality of the information; or\n>\n> \\(iv\\) as required by applicable law, regulation, court order, subpoena, or other compulsory legal process.\n\nIn the event that Delano is compelled by legal process to disclose any information subject to this confidentiality provision, Delano shall provide Greenleaf with prompt written notice","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_51659715-f35c-4612-abeb-9bb18e5d085b","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have enough evidence. Let me synthesize the diagnosis.\n\n**Diagnosis:**\n\nThe iter1 edit added a one-shot enforced **completeness review** in `agent_loop.py`. It *helps* on coverage tasks (+0.13 on cannabis permit, +0.117 on paid-leave, +0.115 on development agreement) — those are enumerate-and-cover tasks where re-reading to fill gaps directly adds graded points. But it **harmed** several tasks (-0.10 litigation invoice, -0.075 arbitration, -0.073 CIM teaser) where the lost criteria are **analytical-depth / interaction / dollar-calc** criteria, not coverage. And the worst task (environmental ESA, stuck at 0.15) it barely moved.\n\n**Key insight on the stuck/worst task (employment, environmental):** Many failed criteria require applying an **internal policy / controlling standard** that lives *inside* a source document the agent must locate and mine — not just \"read every doc.\" The employment rubric requires applying \"Greenleaf internal settlement policy\" ($25k liquidated damages, 12-mo non-compete cap, mutual confidentiality, no-re-employment, dates/title-only references, 409A). The draft agreement and xlsx contain some hooks but the *policy rules* the rubric grades on must be inferred/located from the record. The agent's deliverable is missing the liquidated-damages insertion, the 12-month non-compete reduction, the re-employment strike, the reference rewrite, 409A savings clause, IP assignment — i.e. **the agent identified surface issues but didn't draft the required revisions keyed to the controlling policy.**\n\nThe environmental ESA task (0.15) is an extreme case: the agent must classify each issue by the *correct ASTM E1527-21 category* (REC vs data gap vs ASTM deviation), cite the specific regulatory date (Feb 13 2024), and connect to BFPP defense — i.e. apply a **controlling technical standard** with precision. The agent produced a memo about a *different property's* facts in places and missed the category classifications.\n\n**Dominant fixable failure mode (cross-task, method-addressable):** The agent does the *coverage* pass (list issues) but under-applies the **controlling standard/policy** that the rubric grades against — it fails to (a) identify *which* document/standard is controlling for the task, (b) classify each issue *against that standard's defined categories*, and (c) for markup/revision tasks, *draft the actual conforming revision* keyed to the policy requirement (with the specific number/term the policy states). This is \"method\" gap that prose hasn't reached and that the existing completeness audit (which says \"fill gaps, don't fabricate\") doesn't direct at *classification + drafted revisions keyed to the controlling standard*.\n\nLet me confirm the regression is real and not noise by checking whether the regressed tasks share this \"analytical/revision depth\" character vs coverage. They do. The completeness review likely *harmed* them by burning turns re-reading and re-converting docx (the arbitration transcript shows it spent ~17 turns fighting pandoc reflow) without adding the analytical depth, and possibly introduced churn. \n\nGiven one iteration, the highest-leverage **generic, method-not-memorization** edit: strengthen the system prompt's *method* to explicitly direct (1) identifying the controlling standard/policy/authority for the task and reading it fully, (2) classifying every issue against that authority's defined categories, and (3) for revision/markup tasks, drafting each conforming revision keyed to the specific requirement (number/term) the authority states. This is prose (lowest rung), targets the dominant mode, and is generic. But CLAUDE.md warns prose may be skipped — and the existing prompt already says \"enumerate issues, cross-check.\" The *missing* method element is **classification against the controlling authority + drafted conforming revisions**.\n\nLet me make the edit and run a quick validation experiment."}],"model":"accounts/fireworks/models/glm-5p2","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2243dbd6-f247-49ae-9765-e42e664078a9","uuid":"dfddf07c-c81a-44d9-9d28-36c7013019ff"}
