{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_c9ad622b-76aa-4208-acc3-8c4ac8d99f6e","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"chatcmpl-tool-ac23f333efb71540","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd /workspace/scratch/runs/employment-labor_draft-markup-of-settlement-agreement; ls -la; echo \"=== deliverable.md head ===\"; head -40 deliverable.md 2>/dev/null","description":"Check employment deliverable"}}],"model":"accounts/fireworks/models/glm-5p2","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2243dbd6-f247-49ae-9765-e42e664078a9","uuid":"05e9d377-ad8e-4b18-9a80-c41800909339"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-ac23f333efb71540","type":"tool_result","content":"total 128\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 root root   4096 Jun 27 05:38 .\ndrwxr-xr-x 3 root root   4096 Jun 27 05:38 ..\n-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 120149 Jun 27 05:38 deliverable.md\n=== deliverable.md head ===\n### FILE: cover-memo-to-gc.docx\n         PRIVILEGED         AND         CONFIDENTIAL         —         ATTORNEY-CLIENT         COMMUNICATION         /         ATTORNEY         WORK         PRODUCT  \n       COVER MEMORANDUM  \n          TO:         Tyler Huang, General Counsel, Greenleaf Organic Foods, Inc.  \n          FROM:         Employment Counsel for Greenleaf Organic Foods, Inc.  \n          DATE:         May 12, 2025  \n          RE:         Review of Draft Settlement Agreement and General Release of All Claims (Marcus R. Delano) — Redline Markup and Issues/Risk Summary  \n          PRIVILEGED AND CONFIDENTIAL | ATTORNEY-CLIENT COMMUNICATION | ATTORNEY WORK PRODUCT  \n          Enclosure:            settlement-agreement-markup.docx         (redline of the draft prepared by Engel & Associates, P.C., counsel for Mr. Delano)  \n      \n       I. Executive Summary  \n      You asked us to review the draft Settlement Agreement and General Release of All Claims (the         “    Draft    ”    ) circulated by Mr. Delano’s counsel (Engel & Associates, P.C.) against Greenleaf’s controlling company policies — principally the             Greenleaf 2021 Equity Incentive Plan         (the         “    Equity Plan    ”    ) — and the employment records summarized in the Delano employment summary (the         “    Records    ”    ). The accompanying redline markup inserts conforming revisions as native Word tracked changes.  \n      The Draft is a workable framework but contains a number of provisions that             do not conform to the controlling authorities         and several             missing provisions         that any enforceable settlement of an age-discrimination and whistleblower-retaliation claim should contain. The most important points:  \n             OWBPA nonconformance (critical).         Mr. Delano is 58 years old and is releasing Age Discrimination in Employment Act (    “    ADEA    ”    ) claims. The Draft gives him only             14 days         to consider the agreement, contains             no seven-day revocation period    , defines the         “    Effective Date    ”         as the signing date, and             omits the required advisement to consult an attorney    . Each of these defects can render the ADEA release             invalid and unenforceable         under the Older Workers Benefit Protection Act (    “    OWBPA    ”    ), 29 U.S.C. § 626(f). The redline corrects all four.  \n             Equity Plan nonconformance.         The Draft values the accelerated RSUs at             $10.00/share (the July 1, 2024 409A valuation)    , but the Records show the             most recent 409A valuation, dated January 15, 2025, is $12.50/share    . The Draft’s statement that $10.00 is         “    based on the most recent independent valuation    ”         is inaccurate. The correct value of 5,000 accelerated RSUs is             $62,500, not $50,000    , and the corrected total settlement value is             $537,500, not $525,000    . The Draft also omits the             Compensation Committee approval         that the Equity Plan makes a condition of discretionary accelerated vesting, and does not acknowledge the             forfeiture         of the unvested RSUs on termination. The redline corrects all three.  \n             Whistleblower / DTSA nonconformance.         The confidentiality and non-disparagement clauses, as written, can be read to bar Mr. Delano from reporting the very cold-chain safety concerns that underlie his claims or from cooperating with the             pending Oregon OSHA investigation    , and they omit the             DTSA immunity notice         required by 18 U.S.C. § 1833(b). The redline adds the required carve-outs and notice.  \n             Non-compete enforceability risk.         The 18-month non-compete is imposed             post-termination in the settlement itself    , includes             California         (where non-competes are void), and is broader than ORS 653.295 permits in several respects. The redline narrows it, but             serious enforceability doubt remains         (see Part IV) and we recommend you consider whether to retain it at all.  \n             Significant litigation risk the Records reveal.         The Records show that Greenleaf hired             Raj Mehta (Senior Director of Supply Chain & Logistics) on March 20, 2025 — six days after Mr. Delano’s March 14, 2025 termination — at $185,000    . A replacement hire within days directly contradicts the stated         “    elimination of position due to restructuring    ”         rationale and is powerful evidence of pretext and retaliation. This materially increases the value and risk of Mr. Delano’s claims and is a strong reason to             consummate this settlement         rather than litigate.  \n             EPLI and OSHA exposure.         The settlement should be             tendered to and coordinated with Greenleaf’s EPLI carrier (Timberline Insurance Group, Policy No. TIG-EPL-2024-00391)    , whose consent to settle may be required. Separately, the settlement resolves only Mr. Delano’s             personal         claims; the             Oregon OSHA investigation (opened January 22, 2025) remains open    , and Greenleaf remains exposed to OSHA enforcement on the underlying cold-chain issues.  \n      The balance of this memo (Part III) enumerates each issue, classifies it against the controlling authority, and identifies the conforming revision made in the redline. Part IV addresses strategic and litigation risks that require your action but are not redlined. Part V lists recommended next steps.  \n      \n        II. Controlling Authorities Applied  \n                          Authority  \n          Source  \n          Relevance  \n            Greenleaf 2021 Equity Incentive Plan  \n          Records,         “    Equity Details    ”  \n          Forfeiture of unvested RSUs on termination (other than death/disability/Change of Control); Compensation Committee discretion to approve accelerated vesting in separation agreements; 409A fair-market-value valuations  \n            OWBPA / ADEA, 29 U.S.C. § 626(f)  \n          Statute (cited in Draft §5)  \n          21-day consideration period, 7-day revocation period, written advisement to consult counsel, consideration exceeding prior entitlements — all required for a valid ADEA release by an individual (non-group) terminated employee  \n            ORS 653.295  \n          Oregon statute  \n          Requirements for enforceable non-competition covenants (salary threshold, 18-month cap, notice at hire/advancement, written notice within 30 days of termination)  \n            California Bus. & Prof. Code § 16600  \n          California statute  \n          Voids post-employment non-competes except on sale of business  \n            ORS 654.062(5)  \n          Oregon statute  \n          Whistleblower/retaliation protection for reporting safety concerns (the claim being released)","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2243dbd6-f247-49ae-9765-e42e664078a9","uuid":"75c6b5bb-7102-4f3a-8158-751319f3d55c","timestamp":"2026-06-27T05:48:32.136Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"total 128\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 root root   4096 Jun 27 05:38 .\ndrwxr-xr-x 3 root root   4096 Jun 27 05:38 ..\n-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 120149 Jun 27 05:38 deliverable.md\n=== deliverable.md head ===\n### FILE: cover-memo-to-gc.docx\n         PRIVILEGED         AND         CONFIDENTIAL         —         ATTORNEY-CLIENT         COMMUNICATION         /         ATTORNEY         WORK         PRODUCT  \n       COVER MEMORANDUM  \n          TO:         Tyler Huang, General Counsel, Greenleaf Organic Foods, Inc.  \n          FROM:         Employment Counsel for Greenleaf Organic Foods, Inc.  \n          DATE:         May 12, 2025  \n          RE:         Review of Draft Settlement Agreement and General Release of All Claims (Marcus R. Delano) — Redline Markup and Issues/Risk Summary  \n          PRIVILEGED AND CONFIDENTIAL | ATTORNEY-CLIENT COMMUNICATION | ATTORNEY WORK PRODUCT  \n          Enclosure:            settlement-agreement-markup.docx         (redline of the draft prepared by Engel & Associates, P.C., counsel for Mr. Delano)  \n      \n       I. Executive Summary  \n      You asked us to review the draft Settlement Agreement and General Release of All Claims (the         “    Draft    ”    ) circulated by Mr. Delano’s counsel (Engel & Associates, P.C.) against Greenleaf’s controlling company policies — principally the             Greenleaf 2021 Equity Incentive Plan         (the         “    Equity Plan    ”    ) — and the employment records summarized in the Delano employment summary (the         “    Records    ”    ). The accompanying redline markup inserts conforming revisions as native Word tracked changes.  \n      The Draft is a workable framework but contains a number of provisions that             do not conform to the controlling authorities         and several             missing provisions         that any enforceable settlement of an age-discrimination and whistleblower-retaliation claim should contain. The most important points:  \n             OWBPA nonconformance (critical).         Mr. Delano is 58 years old and is releasing Age Discrimination in Employment Act (    “    ADEA    ”    ) claims. The Draft gives him only             14 days         to consider the agreement, contains             no seven-day revocation period    , defines the         “    Effective Date    ”         as the signing date, and             omits the required advisement to consult an attorney    . Each of these defects can render the ADEA release             invalid and unenforceable         under the Older Workers Benefit Protection Act (    “    OWBPA    ”    ), 29 U.S.C. § 626(f). The redline corrects all four.  \n             Equity Plan nonconformance.         The Draft values the accelerated RSUs at             $10.00/share (the July 1, 2024 409A valuation)    , but the Records show the             most recent 409A valuation, dated January 15, 2025, is $12.50/share    . The Draft’s statement that $10.00 is         “    based on the most recent independent valuation    ”         is inaccurate. The correct value of 5,000 accelerated RSUs is             $62,500, not $50,000    , and the corrected total settlement value is             $537,500, not $525,000    . The Draft also omits the             Compensation Committee approval         that the Equity Plan makes a condition of discretionary accelerated vesting, and does not acknowledge the             forfeiture         of the unvested RSUs on termination. The redline corrects all three.  \n             Whistleblower / DTSA nonconformance.         The confidentiality and non-disparagement clauses, as written, can be read to bar Mr. Delano from reporting the very cold-chain safety concerns that underlie his claims or from cooperating with the             pending Oregon OSHA investigation    , and they omit the             DTSA immunity notice         required by 18 U.S.C. § 1833(b). The redline adds the required carve-outs and notice.  \n             Non-compete enforceability risk.         The 18-month non-compete is imposed             post-termination in the settlement itself    , includes             California         (where non-competes are void), and is broader than ORS 653.295 permits in several respects. The redline narrows it, but             serious enforceability doubt remains         (see Part IV) and we recommend you consider whether to retain it at all.  \n             Significant litigation risk the Records reveal.         The Records show that Greenleaf hired             Raj Mehta (Senior Director of Supply Chain & Logistics) on March 20, 2025 — six days after Mr. Delano’s March 14, 2025 termination — at $185,000    . A replacement hire within days directly contradicts the stated         “    elimination of position due to restructuring    ”         rationale and is powerful evidence of pretext and retaliation. This materially increases the value and risk of Mr. Delano’s claims and is a strong reason to             consummate this settlement         rather than litigate.  \n             EPLI and OSHA exposure.         The settlement should be             tendered to and coordinated with Greenleaf’s EPLI carrier (Timberline Insurance Group, Policy No. TIG-EPL-2024-00391)    , whose consent to settle may be required. Separately, the settlement resolves only Mr. Delano’s             personal         claims; the             Oregon OSHA investigation (opened January 22, 2025) remains open    , and Greenleaf remains exposed to OSHA enforcement on the underlying cold-chain issues.  \n      The balance of this memo (Part III) enumerates each issue, classifies it against the controlling authority, and identifies the conforming revision made in the redline. Part IV addresses strategic and litigation risks that require your action but are not redlined. Part V lists recommended next steps.  \n      \n        II. Controlling Authorities Applied  \n                          Authority  \n          Source  \n          Relevance  \n            Greenleaf 2021 Equity Incentive Plan  \n          Records,         “    Equity Details    ”  \n          Forfeiture of unvested RSUs on termination (other than death/disability/Change of Control); Compensation Committee discretion to approve accelerated vesting in separation agreements; 409A fair-market-value valuations  \n            OWBPA / ADEA, 29 U.S.C. § 626(f)  \n          Statute (cited in Draft §5)  \n          21-day consideration period, 7-day revocation period, written advisement to consult counsel, consideration exceeding prior entitlements — all required for a valid ADEA release by an individual (non-group) terminated employee  \n            ORS 653.295  \n          Oregon statute  \n          Requirements for enforceable non-competition covenants (salary threshold, 18-month cap, notice at hire/advancement, written notice within 30 days of termination)  \n            California Bus. & Prof. Code § 16600  \n          California statute  \n          Voids post-employment non-competes except on sale of business  \n            ORS 654.062(5)  \n          Oregon statute  \n          Whistleblower/retaliation protection for reporting safety concerns (the claim being released)","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
