{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-bb25f13ec32610b4","type":"tool_result","content":"15:             Equity Plan nonconformance.         The Draft values the accelerated RSUs at             $10.00/share (the July 1, 2024 409A valuation)    , but the Records show the             most recent 409A valuation, dated January 15, 2025, is $12.50/share    . The Draft’s statement that $10.00 is         “    based on the most recent independent valuation    ”         is inaccurate. The correct value of 5,000 accelerated RSUs is             $62,500, not $50,000    , and the corrected total settlement value is             $537,500, not $525,000    . The Draft also omits the             Compensation Committee approval         that the Equity Plan makes a condition of discretionary accelerated vesting, and does not acknowledge the             forfeiture         of the unvested RSUs on termination. The redline corrects all three.  \n86:          F1. Back-pay amount inconsistent with the stated period.             Classification: Internal inconsistency / wage-statement risk.         Draft §3(b) pays             $125,000         as back pay         “    representing lost wages from the Separation Date through the Effective Date    ”         — a period of only about             52 days         (March 14 – May 5, 2025), which at Mr. Delano’s $218,000 annual salary equates to roughly             $31,000         of wages. Reporting $125,000 as W-2         “    back pay    ”         for a 52-day period implies an annualized wage far above his salary and invites wage-statement/tax scrutiny.             Revision:         §3(b) recharacterized to include             lost wages, the unpaid 2024 performance bonus (target $43,600, not determined or paid before termination), and the value of lost benefits and other compensation         through the Effective Date.             Action item:         verify the components support $125,000 (see Part IV).  \n99:          I2. Section 8 — Tax provisions (compliant).         The tax characterization (§3(a) $275,000 as 1099-MISC non-wage; §3(b) $125,000 as W-2 wages with FICA/federal/Oregon withholding; §3(c) $75,000 as 1099-NEC to counsel; §3(d) RSUs per the Equity Plan) is internally consistent, and the no-tax-indemnity / each-party-bears-its-own-tax language is appropriate.             No revision         (subject to the RSU valuation correction in D1 and the back-pay recharacterization in F1).  \n113:          R6. Back-pay components should be verified.         The $125,000 back-pay figure should be reconciled to documented components (lost wages through the Effective Date, the unpaid 2024 bonus, and the value of lost benefits). If the components do not support $125,000, consider recharacterizing the excess as additional compensatory damages (1099-MISC) to avoid wage-statement inconsistency.  \n161:- **Equity Plan nonconformance.** The Draft values the accelerated RSUs at **$10.00/share (the July 1, 2024 409A valuation)**, but the Records show the **most recent 409A valuation, dated January 15, 2025, is $12.50/share**. The Draft's statement that $10.00 is \"based on the most recent independent valuation\" is inaccurate. The correct value of 5,000 accelerated RSUs is **$62,500, not $50,000**, and the corrected total settlement value is **$537,500, not $525,000**. The Draft also omits the **Compensation Committee approval** that the Equity Plan makes a condition of discretionary accelerated vesting, and does not acknowledge the **forfeiture** of the unvested RSUs on termination. The redline corrects all three.\n250:**F1. Back-pay amount inconsistent with the stated period.** *Classification: Internal inconsistency / wage-statement risk.* Draft §3(b) pays **$125,000** as back pay \"representing lost wages from the Separation Date through the Effective Date\" — a period of only about **52 days** (March 14 – May 5, 2025), which at Mr. Delano's $218,000 annual salary equates to roughly **$31,000** of wages. Reporting $125,000 as W-2 \"back pay\" for a 52-day period implies an annualized wage far above his salary and invites wage-statement/tax scrutiny. *Revision:* §3(b) recharacterized to include **lost wages, the unpaid 2024 performance bonus (target $43,600, not determined or paid before termination), and the value of lost benefits and other compensation** through the Effective Date. *Action item:* verify the components support $125,000 (see Part IV).\n276:**I2. Section 8 — Tax provisions (compliant).** The tax characterization (§3(a) $275,000 as 1099-MISC non-wage; §3(b) $125,000 as W-2 wages with FICA/federal/Oregon withholding; §3(c) $75,000 as 1099-NEC to counsel; §3(d) RSUs per the Equity Plan) is internally consistent, and the no-tax-indemnity / each-party-bears-its-own-tax language is appropriate. *No revision* (subject to the RSU valuation correction in D1 and the back-pay recharacterization in F1).\n304:**R6. Back-pay components should be verified.** The $125,000 back-pay figure should be reconciled to documented components (lost wages through the Effective Date, the unpaid 2024 bonus, and the value of lost benefits). If the components do not support $125,000, consider recharacterizing the excess as additional compensatory damages (1099-MISC) to avoid wage-statement inconsistency.\n368:             (b) Back Pay.          Greenleaf shall pay to Delano the sum of One Hundred Twenty-Five Thousand Dollars ($125,000.00)           as back pay representing lost wages from the Separation Date through the Effective Date.           as back pay representing lost wages, the unpaid 2024 performance bonus that was not determined or paid prior to Delano's termination, and the value of lost benefits and other compensation, in each case from the Separation Date through the Effective Date.           This amount shall be treated as wage income and shall be subject to all applicable federal, state, and local payroll tax withholdings, including without limitation FICA (Social Security and Medicare), federal income tax withholding, and Oregon state income tax withholding. Greenleaf shall report this payment on IRS Form W-2 for the applicable tax year. Payment of the net amount (after all applicable withholdings) shall be made within fourteen (14) calendar days of the Effective Date by the same method described in Section 3(a).  \n371:             (e) Total Settlement Value.          The aggregate Settlement Payment under this Agreement is           Five Hundred Twenty-Five Thousand Dollars ($525,000.00), comprised of the compensatory damages payment ($275,000.00), the back pay payment ($125,000.00), the attorney fees payment ($75,000.00), and the RSU acceleration ($50,000.00).           Five Hundred Thirty-Seven Thousand Five Hundred Dollars ($537,500.00), comprised of the compensatory damages payment ($275,000.00), the back pay payment ($125,000.00), the attorney fees payment ($75,000.00), and the RSU acceleration ($62,500.00).   \n=== liquidated damages context ===\n102:          I5. Section 12 — Mutual release by Greenleaf (compliant; favorable).         Greenleaf’s release of Delano is appropriately limited by carve-outs for (i) Delano’s fraud/embezzlement/criminal conduct discovered after the Effective Date, (ii) breach of this Agreement, and (iii) surviving obligations under prior agreements. This protects Greenleaf.             No revision.  \n282:**I5. Section 12 — Mutual release by Greenleaf (compliant; favorable).** Greenleaf's release of Delano is appropriately limited by carve-outs for (i) Delano's fraud/embezzlement/criminal conduct discovered after the Effective Date, (ii) breach of this Agreement, and (iii) surviving obligations under prior agreements. This protects Greenleaf. *No revision.*\n389:             (xiv) any and all claims arising under common law, including but not limited to breach of contract (express or implied), breach of the implied covenant of good faith and fair dealing, tortious interference, defamation, slander, libel, fraud, fraudulent inducement, negligent misrepresentation, negligence, wrongful discharge, intentional infliction of emotional distress, negligent infliction of emotional distress, invasion of privacy, and promissory estoppel.  \n412:            Neither Party shall, at any time after the Effective Date, make, publish, or communicate, or cause or encourage any other person or entity to make, publish, or communicate, any disparaging, defamatory, derogatory, or negative statements, whether written or oral, about the other Party, including but not limited to statements regarding the other Party's business practices, products, services, financial condition, management, employees, corporate governance, or the circumstances of Delano's employment with or separation from Greenleaf. For purposes of this Section 7, \"Greenleaf\" includes its officers, directors, and members of senior management, specifically including Sandra Wojcik (CEO), Tyler Huang (General Counsel), Patricia Engel (COO), and Leanne Foss (HR Director), each in their individual and official capacities.           Any breach of this non-disparagement provision shall entitle the non-breaching Party to seek injunctive relief and all other available legal and equitable remedies. The obligations set forth in this Section 7 shall survive the expiration or termination of this Agreement and shall continue in perpetuity.           Nothing in this Section 7 shall prohibit either Party from making truthful statements to any governmental agency or regulatory authority, or from making truthful statements in response to a subpoena, court order, or other compulsory legal process, or in connection with any legal proceeding between the Parties to enforce or challenge this Agreement. Any breach of this non-disparagement provision shall entitle the non-breaching Party to seek injunctive relief and all other available legal and equitable remedies. The obligations set forth in this Section 7 shall survive the expiration or termination of this Agreement and shall continue for a period of three (3) years following the Effective Date.   \n424:            In the event that Delano breaches this non-competition provision, Greenleaf shall be entitled to seek injunctive relief, specific performance, and all other available legal and equitable remedies, including recovery of damages sustained as a result of such breach.           In addition, the eighteen (18) month non-competition period shall be tolled during any period during which Delano is in breach of this provision, and shall resume upon the date on which such breach ceases.           In addition, the eighteen (18) month non-competition period shall be tolled during any period during which Delano is in breach of this provision, and shall resume upon the date on which such breach ceases; provided, however, that in no event shall the aggregate restricted period (including any tolled period) exceed eighteen (18) months, consistent with the duration limit of ORS 653.295(1)(c).   \n433:            Greenleaf, on behalf of itself and each of the Releasees, hereby irrevocably and unconditionally releases, acquits, and forever discharges Delano from any and all claims, demands, actions, causes of action, suits, damages, losses, expenses, and liabilities of every kind and nature, whether known or unknown, suspected or unsuspected, that Greenleaf has, has ever had, or may hereafter have against Delano, arising out of, related to, or in any way connected with Delano's employment with Greenleaf or the termination thereof, from the beginning of time through the Effective Date, except for claims arising from: (i) Delano's fraud, embezzlement, or criminal conduct discovered after the Effective Date; (ii) Delano's breach of any provision of this Agreement; or (iii) any obligation of Delano that survives termination of employment under any prior written agreement between the Parties, to the extent that such obligation is not superseded by this Agreement.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2243dbd6-f247-49ae-9765-e42e664078a9","uuid":"bb44bf06-ecde-43ce-912f-9acaf8a6f1df","timestamp":"2026-06-27T05:48:38.725Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"15:             Equity Plan nonconformance.         The Draft values the accelerated RSUs at             $10.00/share (the July 1, 2024 409A valuation)    , but the Records show the             most recent 409A valuation, dated January 15, 2025, is $12.50/share    . The Draft’s statement that $10.00 is         “    based on the most recent independent valuation    ”         is inaccurate. The correct value of 5,000 accelerated RSUs is             $62,500, not $50,000    , and the corrected total settlement value is             $537,500, not $525,000    . The Draft also omits the             Compensation Committee approval         that the Equity Plan makes a condition of discretionary accelerated vesting, and does not acknowledge the             forfeiture         of the unvested RSUs on termination. The redline corrects all three.  \n86:          F1. Back-pay amount inconsistent with the stated period.             Classification: Internal inconsistency / wage-statement risk.         Draft §3(b) pays             $125,000         as back pay         “    representing lost wages from the Separation Date through the Effective Date    ”         — a period of only about             52 days         (March 14 – May 5, 2025), which at Mr. Delano’s $218,000 annual salary equates to roughly             $31,000         of wages. Reporting $125,000 as W-2         “    back pay    ”         for a 52-day period implies an annualized wage far above his salary and invites wage-statement/tax scrutiny.             Revision:         §3(b) recharacterized to include             lost wages, the unpaid 2024 performance bonus (target $43,600, not determined or paid before termination), and the value of lost benefits and other compensa