{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-b7bb18e136c591a1","type":"tool_result","content":"### FILE: environmental-issues-memo.docx\n          ENVIRONMENTAL DUE DILIGENCE ISSUES MEMORANDUM  \n          PRIVILEGED & CONFIDENTIAL — ATTORNEY WORK PRODUCT / DUE DILIGENCE DELIVERABLE  \n                          To:  \n          Cornerstone Industrial Partners LLC — Deal Team (Marcus Choi, Managing Partner); Whitfield & Crane LLP (Sarah Castellano, lead partner; David Morales, associate)  \n                From:  \n          Environmental Due Diligence Review  \n                Date:  \n          October 28, 2024  \n                Re:  \n          Environmental Issues and Severity Ratings — Proposed Acquisition of 4820 Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Toledo, Lucas County, Ohio 43611 (Lucas County Parcel Nos. 18-04562-001, -002, -003) from Breckenridge Manufacturing Co.; Loan No. GLCB-2024-08173  \n                Transaction:  \n          Asset Purchase Agreement dated September 1, 2024; Purchase Price $8,750,000; Great Lakes Capital Bank loan $6,125,000; Closing Date December 15, 2024  \n         \n       1.0 EXECUTIVE SUMMARY  \n      This memorandum identifies, classifies, and severity-rates the environmental issues raised by the Phase I Environmental Site Assessment (    “    Phase I ESA    ”    ) prepared by Greenfield Environmental Consultants Inc. (    “    Greenfield    ”    ) dated October 25, 2024 (site reconnaissance October 2, 2024) and the supporting environmental and transactional documents for the proposed acquisition of 4820 Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Toledo, Ohio (the         “    Property    ”    ) from Breckenridge Manufacturing Co. (    “    Seller    ”         or         “    Breckenridge    ”    ).  \n      The Greenfield Phase I ESA identifies             two on-site recognized environmental conditions (        “        RECs        ”        )    : (1) former trichloroethylene (    “    TCE    ”    ) vapor-degreasing operations and an abandoned, leaking waste-TCE drum; and (2) former hexavalent-chromium and nickel electroplating operations. Both RECs are confirmed and supported by the record, and both warrant the recommended Phase II investigation.  \n      However, the review identifies a             material gap in the Phase I ESA’s findings    : the documented tetrachloroethylene (    “    PCE    ”    ) groundwater contamination plume migrating onto the Property from the former Lake Erie Dry Cleaning facility at 4900 Lakeshore Industrial Drive (120 feet upgradient; PCE at 87 µg/L, 17.4× the Ohio standard of 5 µg/L; the Property is within a designated Ohio EPA Groundwater Management Zone) is             not classified as a REC         in the report’s findings, notwithstanding the Lender’s express instruction that any off-site plume migrating toward the Property         “    must be identified as recognized environmental conditions.    ”         This is the single most significant issue in the file and is rated             Critical    .  \n      The review further identifies (i) additional on-site conditions that appear to be omitted or misclassified RECs/data gaps (an unregistered 2,000-gallon waste-solvent UST, an undocumented monitoring well, and the east-side outdoor drum-storage area that was the subject of a 2003 Ohio EPA Notice of Violation); (ii) multiple Seller representation inaccuracies under §§4.12–4.13 of the Asset Purchase Agreement (the         “    APA    ”    ); and (iii) a cluster of mandatory Lender conditions that are triggered by the presence of RECs and have not yet been satisfied.  \n          Two time-critical items require immediate attention:  \n             The Environmental Due Diligence Period expires at 5:00 p.m. ET on October 31, 2024.         Under APA §6.3(b), Buyer may terminate and recover its $437,500 earnest money if the Phase I identifies RECs that         “    could result in Remediation Costs exceeding $500,000.    ”         The identified RECs (TCE, hexavalent chromium, and the off-site PCE plume) plausibly exceed that threshold. If Buyer does not deliver a termination notice by October 31, 2024, the termination right is             deemed waived         (APA §6.3(c)), although indemnification rights under Article VIII survive.  \n             The Lender will not fund on the Phase I alone.         Identification of RECs triggers the Lender’s mandatory Phase II / environmental-insurance / escrow / vapor-intrusion requirements, with deliverables due no later than November 30, 2024.  \n      A total of             fifty-two (52) distinct issues         are catalogued below, rated Critical (3), High (16), Medium (17), and Low (16).  \n      \n        2.0 SCOPE AND DOCUMENTS REVIEWED  \n       2.1 The Proposed Acquisition (In-Scope)  \n      The         “    proposed acquisition    ”         is the transaction documented in the Asset Purchase Agreement dated September 1, 2024, by and between Breckenridge Manufacturing Co. (Seller) and Cornerstone Industrial Partners LLC (Buyer), for the Property at 4820 Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Toledo, Ohio, financed by a $6,125,000 acquisition loan from Great Lakes Capital Bank (the         “    Lender    ”    ). The following five documents were reviewed and form the basis of this memorandum:  \n                          Document  \n          Date  \n          Author / Source  \n            Phase I Environmental Site Assessment (Greenfield Project No. GEC-2024-0347)  \n          October 25, 2024 (recon. October 2, 2024)  \n          Greenfield Environmental Consultants Inc.  \n            Asset Purchase Agreement — Excerpt (Articles I, IV §§4.12–4.13, VI §6.3, VIII §§8.1–8.4; Schedule 4.13)  \n          September 1, 2024  \n          Breckenridge / Cornerstone  \n            Environmental Due Diligence Requirements Letter (Loan No. GLCB-2024-08173)  \n          September 10, 2024  \n          Great Lakes Capital Bank (Janet Pham)  \n            Ohio EPA Records-Response Letter (File Ref. DERR-NW-2024-RR-0438)  \n          September 28, 2024  \n          Ohio EPA, DERR, Northwest District Office (Thomas Kessler)  \n            EDR Radius Map Report — Database Summary (EDR Inquiry No. 6742891)  \n          September 15, 2024  \n          Environmental Data Resources, Inc.  \n           2.2 Out-of-Scope Documents (Separate Transaction)  \n      Three additional documents in the diligence file pertain to a             separate, unrelated Cornerstone acquisition         of 2850 Millrace Road, Dayton, Ohio (seller: Valtec Manufacturing Holdings Inc.; purchase price $4,200,000; counsel: Bridgewell & Hatch LLP; no Great Lakes Capital Bank loan). These documents were reviewed and             confirmed not to bear on the Toledo acquisition    :  \n              Phase I ESA — 2850 Millrace Road, Dayton         (Terravista Environmental Consulting Inc., dated April 18, 2025; prepared to ASTM             E1527-13    , the superseded prior edition);  \n              UST Closure Report — 2850 Millrace Road, Dayton         (Redland Environmental Services, dated November 12, 2004); and  \n              GeoSearch Environmental Database Search Summary — 2850 Millrace Road, Dayton         (GeoSearch Data Systems, dated March 28, 2025).  \n      These are addressed in Section 6.10 (Out-of-Scope) for file-management purposes only. Notably, the Dayton Phase I ESA was prepared to the             superseded ASTM E1527-13         standard, whereas the Toledo Phase I ESA correctly conforms to the current             ASTM E1527-21         standard required by both the APA and the Lender.  \n      \n         3.0 CONTROLLING AUTHORITIES AND KEY REQUIREMENTS  \n      Each issue below is classified against, and must be conformed to, the following controlling authorities:  \n       3.1 ASTM E1527-21 (Controlling Technical Standard)  \n      The APA (§1.1) and the Lender (§2 of the lender letter) both require the Phase I ESA to conform to             ASTM E1527-21    ,             Standard Practice for Environmental Site Assessments: Phase I Environmental Site Assessment Process    , and to satisfy the All Appropriate Inquiries (    “    AAI    ”    ) rule at 40 C.F.R. Part 312. The Greenfield report states conformance to E1527-21. Defined categories under E1527-21 include:             REC         (§3.2.78),             CREC    ,             HREC    ,             de minimis condition    , and             data gap         (§3.2.25 / §7.1.2). A REC includes the presence or likely presence of hazardous substances         “    in, on, or at a property    ”         due to a release, conditions indicative of a release, or a material threat of a future release — including migration onto the property from an off-site source.  \n        3.2 40 C.F.R. Part 312 (AAI Rule)  \n      The federal AAI rule (required by APA §6.3(a) and Lender §4) governs the inquiries necessary to qualify Buyer (and the Lender) for the CERCLA bona fide prospective purchaser, innocent landowner, and contiguous property owner defenses. The Environmental Professional (    “    EP    ”    ) must meet the qualifications of 40 C.F.R. §312.10.  \n        3.3 Great Lakes Capital Bank Environmental Risk Policy (Policy No. ERP-2021-04, amended January 1, 2023)  \n      Set forth in the September 10, 2024 lender letter, this is the controlling authority for loan-condition compliance. Key mandatory requirements and numeric thresholds:","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2243dbd6-f247-49ae-9765-e42e664078a9","uuid":"76d39b3f-4e22-49fd-9338-2813b0d9c101","timestamp":"2026-06-27T06:02:47.062Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"### FILE: environmental-issues-memo.docx\n          ENVIRONMENTAL DUE DILIGENCE ISSUES MEMORANDUM  \n          PRIVILEGED & CONFIDENTIAL — ATTORNEY WORK PRODUCT / DUE DILIGENCE DELIVERABLE  \n                          To:  \n          Cornerstone Industrial Partners LLC — Deal Team (Marcus Choi, Managing Partner); Whitfield & Crane LLP (Sarah Castellano, lead partner; David Morales, associate)  \n                From:  \n          Environmental Due Diligence Review  \n                Date:  \n          October 28, 2024  \n                Re:  \n          Environmental Issues and Severity Ratings — Proposed Acquisition of 4820 Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Toledo, Lucas County, Ohio 43611 (Lucas County Parcel Nos. 18-04562-001, -002, -003) from Breckenridge Manufacturing Co.; Loan No. GLCB-2024-08173  \n                Transaction:  \n          Asset Purchase Agreement dated September 1, 2024; Purchase Price $8,750,000; Great Lakes Capital Bank loan $6,125,000; Closing Date December 15, 2024  \n         \n       1.0 EXECUTIVE SUMMARY  \n      This memorandum identifies, classifies, and severity-rates the environmental issues raised by the Phase I Environmental Site Assessment (    “    Phase I ESA    ”    ) prepared by Greenfield Environmental Consultants Inc. (    “    Greenfield    ”    ) dated October 25, 2024 (site reconnaissance October 2, 2024) and the supporting environmental and transactional documents for the proposed acquisition of 4820 Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Toledo, Ohio (the         “    Property    ”    ) from Breckenridge Manufacturing Co. (    “    Seller    ”         or         “    Breckenridge    ”    ).  \n      The Greenfield Phase I ESA identifies             two on-site recognized environmental conditions (        “        RECs        ”        )    : (1) former trichloroethylene (    “    TCE    ”    ) vapor-degreasing operations and an abandoned, leaking waste-TCE drum; and (2) former hexavalent-chromium and nickel electroplating operations. Both RECs are confirmed and supported by the record, and both warrant the recommended Phase II investigation.  \n      However, the review identifies a             material gap in the Phase I ESA’s findings    : the documented tetrachloroethylene (    “    PCE    ”    ) groundwater contamination plume migrating onto the Property from the former Lake Erie Dry Cleaning facility at 4900 Lakeshore Industrial Drive (120 feet upgradient; PCE at 87 µg/L, 17.4× the Ohio standard of 5 µg/L; the Property is within a designated Ohio EPA Groundwater Management Zone) is             not classified as a REC         in the report’s findings, notwithstanding the Lender’s express instruction that any off-site plume migrating toward the Property         “    must be identified as recognized environmental conditions.    ”         This is the single most significant issue in the file and is rated             Critical    .  \n      The review further identifies (i) additional on-site conditions that appear to be omitted or misclassified RECs/data gaps (an unregistered 2,000-gallon waste-solvent UST, an undocumented monitoring well, and the east-side outdoor drum-storage area that was the subject of a 2003 Ohio EPA Notice of Violation); (ii) multiple Seller representation inaccuracies under §§4.12–4.13 of the Asset Purchase Agreement (the         “    APA    ”    ); and (iii) a cluster of mandatory Lender conditions that are triggered by the presence of RECs and have not yet been satisfied.  \n          Two time-critical items require immediate attention:  \n             The Environmental Due Diligence Period expires at 5:00 p.m. ET on October 31, 2024.         Under APA §6.3(b), Buyer may terminate and recover its $437,500 earnest money if the Phase I identifies RECs that         “    could result in Remediation Costs exceeding $500,000.    ”         The identified RECs (TCE, hexavalent chromium, and the off-site PCE plume) plausibly exceed that threshold. If Buyer does not deliver a termination notice by October 31, 2024, the termination right is             deemed waived         (APA §6.3(c)), although indemnification rights under Article VIII survive.  \n             The Lender will not fund on the Phase I alone.         Identification of RECs triggers the Lender’s mandatory Phase II / environmental-insurance / escrow / vapor-intrusion requirements, with deliverables due no later than November 30, 2024.  \n      A total of             fifty-two (52) distinct issues         are catalogued below, rated Critical (3), High (16), Medium (17), and Low (16).  \n      \n        2.0 SCOPE AND DOCUMENTS REVIEWED  \n       2.1 The Proposed Acquisition (In-Scope)  \n      The         “    proposed acquisition    ”         is the transaction documented in the Asset Purchase Agreement dated September 1, 2024, by and between Breckenridge Manufacturing Co. (Seller) and Cornerstone Industrial Partners LLC (Buyer), for the Property at 4820 Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Toledo, Ohio, financed by a $6,125,000 acquisition loan from Great Lakes Capital Bank (the         “    Lender    ”    ). The following five documents were reviewed and form the basis of this memorandum:  \n                          Document  \n          Date  \n          Author / Source  \n            Phase I Environmental Site Assessment (Greenfield Project No. GEC-2024-0347)  \n          October 25, 2024 (recon. October 2, 2024)  \n          Greenfield Environmental Consultants Inc.  \n            Asset Purchase Agreement — Excerpt (Articles I, IV §§4.12–4.13, VI §6.3, VIII §§8.1–8.4; Schedule 4.13)  \n          September 1, 2024  \n          Breckenridge / Cornerstone  \n            Environmental Due Diligence Requirements Letter (Loan No. GLCB-2024-08173)  \n          September 10, 2024  \n          Great Lakes Capital Bank (Janet Pham)  \n            Ohio EPA Records-Response Letter (File Ref. DERR-NW-2024-RR-0438)  \n          September 28, 2024  \n          Ohio EPA, DERR, Northwest District Office (Thomas Kessler)  \n            EDR Radius Map Report — Database Summary (EDR Inquiry No. 6742891)  \n          September 15, 2024  \n          Environmental Data Resources, Inc.  \n           2.2 Out-of-Scope Documents (Separate Transaction)  \n      Three additional documents in the diligence file pertain to a             separate, unrelated Cornerstone acquisition         of 2850 Millrace Road, Dayton, Ohio (seller: Valtec Manufacturing Holdings Inc.; purchase price $4,200,000; counsel: Bridgewell & Hatch LLP; no Great Lakes Capital Bank loan). These documents were reviewed and             confirmed not to bear on the Toledo acquisition    :  \n              Phase I ESA — 2850 Millrace Road, Dayton         (Terravista Environmental Consulting Inc., dated April 18, 2025; prepared to ASTM             E1527-13    , the superseded prior edition);  \n              UST Closure Report — 2850 Millrace Road, Dayton         (Redland Environmental Services, dated November 12, 2004); and  \n              GeoSearch Environmental Database Search Summary — 2850 Millrace Road, Dayton         (GeoSearch Data Systems, dated March 28, 2025).  \n      These are addressed in Section 6.10 (Out-of-Scope) for file-management purposes only. Notably, the Dayton Phase I ESA was prepared to the             superseded ASTM E1527-13         standard, whereas the Toledo Phase I ESA correctly conforms to the current             ASTM E1527-21         standard required by both the APA and the Lender.  \n      \n         3.0 CONTROLLING AUTHORITIES AND KEY REQUIREMENTS  \n      Each issue below is classified against, and must be conformed to, the following controlling authorities:  \n       3.1 ASTM E1527-21 (Controlling Technical Standard)  \n      The APA (§1.1) and the Lender (§2 of the lender letter) both require the Phase I ESA to conform to             ASTM E1527-21    ,             Standard Practice for Environmental Site Assessments: Phase I Environmental Site Assessment Process    , and to satisfy the All Appropriate Inquiries (    “    AAI    ”    ) rule at 40 C.F.R. Part 312. The Greenfield report states conformance to E1527-21. Defined categories under E1527-21 include:             REC         (§3.2.78),             CREC    ,             HREC    ,             de minimis condition    , and             data gap         (§3.2.25 / §7.1.2). A REC includes the presence or likely presence of hazardous substances         “    in, on, or at a property    ”         due to a release, conditions indicative of a release, or a material threat of a future release — including migration onto the property from an off-site source.  \n        3.2 40 C.F.R. Part 312 (AAI Rule)  \n      The federal AAI rule (required by APA §6.3(a) and Lender §4) governs the inquiries necessary to qualify Buyer (and the Lender) for the CERCLA bona fide prospective purchaser, innocent landowner, and contiguous property owner defenses. The Environmental Professional (    “    EP    ”    ) must meet the qualifications of 40 C.F.R. §312.10.  \n        3.3 Great Lakes Capital Bank Environmental Risk Policy (Policy No. ERP-2021-04, amended January 1, 2023)  \n      Set forth in the September 10, 2024 lender letter, this is the controlling authority for loan-condition compliance. Key mandatory requirements and numeric thresholds:","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
